Rationale: The manuscript presents a compelling empirical contribution by constructing a 50-year panel dataset of the Federal Reserve's Beige Book (1970–2025) and applying modern natural language processing (NLP) to extract qualitative sentiment. The core objective—to demonstrate that qualitative 'soft' information from central bank contacts has systematic predictive power for GDP growth and recessions—is highly promising. However, the independent evaluations from the Econometrician, Data Scientist, and AI Expert reveal a set of co-dependent flaws in both the NLP pipeline and the econometric specifications that collectively undermine the paper's central claims. First, the NLP pipeline applies traditional bag-of-words preprocessing (lowercasing, stop-word removal, and stemming/lemmatization) before feeding the text into FinBERT. This destructive preprocessing is fundamentally incompatible with transformer-based architectures, which rely on full sentence context, word order, and syntactic relations to generate accurate embeddings. Second, the econometric analysis suffers from critical design issues: (a) a timing mismatch in Table 1 that grants the Beige Book sentiment index an unfair information advantage over the Survey of Professional Forecasters (SPF) nowcast; (b) omitted variable bias in Table 6 (Model 2), where dropping Year Fixed Effects causes the 'excluding bank' sentiment variable to proxy for aggregate national shocks rather than true regional spillovers; and (c) a failure to cluster standard errors at the Federal Reserve District level in the panel regressions. Because these issues are highly repairable within the existing data and regression framework, the panel has reached a consensus of MAJOR REVISION. The revision path requires a complete re-running of the NLP pipeline on raw text, followed by a systematic re-estimation of the nowcasting and panel regressions with appropriate timing controls, fixed effects, and clustered standard errors. 
Letter:  Dear Dr. Lee, Thank you for submitting your manuscript to our journal. Your paper compiles an exceptionally valuable, long-run dataset of the Federal Reserve's Beige Book texts spanning over 50 years (1970–2025) and applies a modern, domain-specific transformer model (FinBERT) to extract qualitative economic sentiment. The editorial board and our specialized referees (an Econometrician, a Data Scientist, and an AI Expert) agree that this represents a significant empirical contribution to the literature on qualitative central bank communications and macroeconomic forecasting.However, the review process has identified several critical methodological and econometric flaws that must be addressed before the paper can be considered for publication. These issues are co-dependent, as the flaws in the NLP pipeline directly affect the quality of the independent variables used in your regressions, while the econometric specifications overstate the predictive power and regional spillover effects of the sentiment index. We have outlined these major concerns below:\n\n1. Destructive NLP Preprocessing: On page 6, you state that you convert the text to lowercase, remove numbers and stop words, and tokenize/stem words (e.g., collapsing 'increase', 'increasing', and 'increasingly') prior to applying FinBERT. This traditional bag-of-words preprocessing is highly inappropriate for transformer-based models like BERT. FinBERT relies on self-attention mechanisms, positional encodings, and full sentence context to capture sentiment, negation (e.g., 'not', 'no'), and syntactic relations. Mutilating the text beforehand destroys these contextual cues and violates alignment with FinBERT's pre-trained WordPiece vocabulary, leading to highly degraded and noisy sentiment scores. You must rerun the sentiment extraction by passing the raw, uncleaned text directly to FinBERT's native tokenizer.\n\n2. Nowcasting Timing Mismatch (Table 1): You construct the quarterly Beige Book sentiment series by taking the last observation in each quarter and comparing its nowcasting performance against the SPF nowcast. However, the SPF nowcast is typically released in the middle of the second month of the quarter, whereas the last Beige Book is released much later (late in the third month). This timing mismatch grants your index a substantial information advantage, overstating its relative nowcasting power. To ensure a fair comparison, you must restrict the Beige Book sentiment index to releases that strictly precede or align with the SPF release date. Regional Panel and Omitted Variable Bias (Table 6): In Specification (2), you drop Year Fixed Effects and include 'Beige Book sentiment (excl. Bank)' to capture regional spillovers. Without controlling for national-level shocks (either via Year FE or explicit national controls like US GDP growth), this variable simply acts as a proxy for the aggregate national business cycle. This is a classic reflection/omitted variable problem rather than a clean measure of regional spillovers. You must reframe this interpretation or include national controls to isolate true spatial spillovers.\n\n4. Panel Inference and Clustering: The panel regressions in Table 6 do not appear to cluster standard errors at the Federal Reserve District level. Given the high likelihood of spatial and temporal autocorrelation in regional economic data, unclustered standard errors are likely severely understated, leading to overinflated t-statistics. You must re-estimate these models with clustered standard errors at the District level.\n\nWe believe the core economic question, your unique dataset, and the forecasting framework are highly salvageable. We therefore invite you to submit a major revision that systematically addresses these concerns.


  minimum_viable_revision_path: To achieve a successful revision, the authors must execute the following steps:\n\n1. Correct the NLP Pipeline: Rerun the FinBERT sentiment extraction by passing the raw, uncleaned Beige Book text (preserving stop words, punctuation, negation cues, and exact word forms) directly into the FinBERT model using its native WordPiece tokenizer. Provide the exact mathematical formula used to aggregate sentence-level sentiment classifications into the quarterly and annual indices.\n\n2. Align Nowcasting Timelines: Re-estimate the nowcasting regressions in Table 1. Ensure that the Beige Book sentiment index only includes observations from releases that occurred prior to (or strictly aligned with) the SPF mid-quarter release date to eliminate any unfair information advantage.\n\n3. Correct Panel Regression Inference: Re-estimate all panel regressions in Table 6 with standard errors clustered at the Federal Reserve District level to ensure valid statistical inference.\n\n4. Resolve Omitted Variable Bias in Spillovers: Re-estimate Table 6, Model 2, by either: (a) including national macroeconomic controls (such as aggregate US GDP growth) alongside the 'excluding bank' sentiment variable, or (b) keeping Year Fixed Effects and finding an alternative identification strategy for spillovers. If national controls are used, explicitly reframe the text to acknowledge that without Year FE, the 'excl. Bank' sentiment captures common national macroeconomic shocks rather than pure regional spillovers.",
  "constructive_summary": "This paper makes a valuable empirical contribution by compiling a 50-year corpus of Federal Reserve Beige Books (1970–2025) and demonstrating that qualitative 'soft' information contains systematic predictive signals for GDP growth and recessions. However, the current manuscript is held back by a destructive NLP preprocessing pipeline that degrades the FinBERT sentiment scores, an unfair timing advantage in the nowcasting comparison against the SPF, and omitted variable bias and unclustered standard errors in the regional panel regressions. These issues are highly repairable. By re-running the NLP pipeline on raw text, aligning the nowcasting timelines, clustering standard errors at the District level, and properly controlling for national shocks in the spillover analysis, the authors can robustly validate their central claims and deliver a high-impact paper at the intersection of economics and machine learning.
